Register now for the 21st Century program!
During NTI, we will be providing one on one (teacher calls) and group (google meet) tutoring/homework help. The program is available to all students (NTI/GCVLT) in grades 2-8 (WES/WMS) and grades 3-8 (AES/GES/MES/MMS). Virtual STEM enrichment, fitness activities, field trips and more will also be provided. Enrichment kits will be sent out monthly with weekly themed activities guided by teachers.
Register below and we will contact you with more information. Program begins September 16, 2020, but you may continue to register and begin participation after that date.

https://docs.google.com/forms/d/1HniQk7ACYLZpvUKT0r5QADbPjBCS7Yv325wcFBndN2g/edit?usp=sharing

D Sean Howard
September 4 at 1:15 PM ¬∑

Due to a student-athlete testing positive for COVID-19, the Boyd County Heath Department and Ashland Blazer High School have agreed that all football related activities at Ashland Blazer High School be postponed until September 15th. This will cancel our September 11th game vs. Greenup County. Our paramount concern is the safety and well being of our student-athletes, staff, and community. Any close contacts will be required to quarantine and will be contacted by Ashland Boyd County Health Department contact tracers.

We are excited to welcome Mindy Crisp, LCSW as our new district mental health provider. Ms. Crisp is currently available for Telehealth services for all GCSD students (NTI and GC Virtual Learning Track). Once school returns to in-person instruction, she will be available for face-to-face services. See below for information on how to contact Ms. Crisp. If your child is already receiving services from another school-contracted provider, we are including their Telehealth contact information in this post as well.
Take care, Musketeers!
#TogetherGC #GCMusketeerWay

post_text:
FOOD DELIVERY UPDATE!

If you have signed up for food delivery for a GC student, the bus will be arriving on Tuesday‚Äôs and Fridays beginning September 8th, 2020 between 9AM-12PM.
Meals will be delivered to bus stops. Parent/guardian or student must be at the bus stop to receive meals. Meals will require refrigeration.
Tuesday delivery for week one will include 4 breakfasts and 3 lunches for K-12 students. Friday delivery will include 2 breakfasts and 2 lunches for K-12 students. Preschool student meals will be adjusted to the number of days enrolled.
To request delivery, you must complete the survey below or call the Central Office at 606-473-9810.
https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSeg-Y-x2pJjJweDBD9wR9qmPjeBJI_FCuh_fEMvi1qWWAPDNQ/viewform?usp=sf_link

If you choose to pick up meals at the school, pick-up is available upon request Tuesday and Friday between the hours of 4PM-6PM. Call Central Office at 606-473-9810 to be added to the pick-up list.

shared_text:
Superintendent Traysea Moresea
August 10 at 4:46 PM ¬∑

Governor Beshear has requested that we do not hold in person classes until after September 28, 2020. We will respect his request that was given to us just this afternoon. I will be honest that we have prepared for many options but the date 9/28/20 was never in the realm of possibilities. This date does not mean we can‚Äôt begin instruction via NTI and the GC Virtual Academy. Our team is working tirelessly to redo the entire action plan and calendar. I know you want and deserve answers. We will provide an update once we have had a moment to reboot, recreate, and share plans with our board of education and employees. Feeling very blessed to work with a dynamic team of leaders and staff who will help make this all work for kids! You will hear more from me tomorrow evening. Greenup Home #GCMusketeerWay #TogetherGC

MMS music teacher, Steffanie Skiles, has received a 2021 Valvoline‚Ñ¢ Teacher Achievement Award (TAA). The Kentucky Department of Education and Valvoline Inc. have selected 24 outstanding Kentucky educators as recipients. These teachers qualify to compete for the 2021 Kentucky Teacher of the Year Award.

Ms. Skiles will be honored at an event in the fall. At that time the Kentucky Elementary, Middle and High School Teachers of the Year will be announced. From this group of three finalists, the Kentucky Teacher of the Year will be named and will represent the state in the National Teacher of the Year competition.

Judging was conducted in May by a blue-ribbon panel of veteran educators, many of whom have more than 25 years of teaching experience. Applications included information on the nominees‚Äô teaching philosophies, teaching experiences and involvement in their respective communities, as well as letters of recommendation from peers, students, parents, administrators and others.

Congratulations, Ms Skiles!
#GCMusketeerWay

post_text: GC Elementary Cross Country Information
shared_text:
Dawndy Wagner‚ÄéGreenup County Elementary Cross Country
July 7 at 8:52 AM ¬∑

Hello! We have started a new group for the start of our new 2020 cross country season! I am happy to finally announce that we can start our preseason practicing this week. If you are already committed to activities no worries I understand life even these days is busy. With that said we will have practice this week on Tuesday July 7th and Thursday 9th at the GCHS track starting at 4:15 p.m. Next week we will meet at the GCHS track on Monday the 13th and Wednesday the 15th at 4:15 p.m. The age range for our team is 5 years old registered in Kindergarten through 6th grade. The child must be willing to attempt to run/jog/walk a full mile. I am aware of the heat index so please bring water and hydrate through out the day before you arrive, we will be in the sun and active for around 35-40 minutes. At the beginning and end of each of these practices I will be happy to answer any questions that your family might have. We will follow all state provided guidelines for the safety and health of all participants. If you have any questions please feel free to let me know.

Today we celebrate the best of the Class of 2020! Congratulations to co-valedictorians, MacKenzie Collins and Kolby Hunt, and salutatorian, Ashley Boggs. These outstanding students set the standard academically while serving as leaders in the school and the community. We are proud to call them Musketeer alumni. All the best to Kenz, Kolby and Ash! Go do great things!
Don't forget that you can hear their commencement speeches next Friday, May 22 at 7:00 (a link to the event will be posted).

Emergency Meals-to-You Application

Greenup Schools
May 4 at 12:39 PM ¬∑

Greenup County Food Service is proud to partner with the USDA and Baylor University to provide free food, through June 30, to all students enrolled in Greenup County Schools.

When you sign up for the free Meals-to-You program, a box of food will be delivered to your home every two-weeks. Boxes will include 10 breakfasts and 10 lunches for each child in your home.

Registration is only available today through Friday May 8. To register, follow the link below. This is a free program that does not interfere with any other programs or assistance which you may be eligible for!

Please use your child‚Äôs lunch number as the student ID or enter 0 (zero) if you don‚Äôt know their number or if they have not been enrolled in school.

If you have any questions, contact Barb at 606-473-9810, ext. 2052 or Rebecca at 606-473-9810 ext. 2010 or call 606-473-9819 and ask for the Food Service Department.

https://mealstoyou.org/emergency-meals-to-you-application/

No matter what has been thrown at them since March 13, they have stepped up, served with pride, and never complained. We are forever indebted to them for their selfless service.
Thank you GCSD food service staff. We love you.

üíôü§çOfficially signing to be a Raider Cheerleaderü§çüíô We watched Carley take her first big adult leap and make a huge decision about her plans for the future in school and cheer. She will be leaving home to go 3 1/2 hours away to achieve her dreams with a cheer scholarship at Lindsey Wilson College in Columbia Kentucky. She will be majoring in Education. Carley‚Äôs faith, determination and heart will make her an awesome teacher. My heart aches that Carley‚Äôs accomplishment couldn‚Äôt have had the proper signing at her school with her peers, teammates, and coaches as I know she so dearly wanted. But maybe we can all celebrate later.. We love you Carley and are so very proud of you and all of your accomplishments. We can‚Äôt wait to watch you Cheer as a Raider at ballgames .

post_text:
Here's the latest update for NTI work.

Don't forget about our free lunch program! Pick up breakfast and lunch at AES, MMS, WMS and GCHS on M-W-F from 11:30-12:30. Anyone 18 and under that is present in vehicle will receive meals. Please have trunk or hatch open if possible for staff to place meals in.

Need access to a Chromebook to complete NTI work? Contact your child's school to join the Chromebook loan program. Parents must sign a contract to replace the Chromebook if it is damaged, lost, or not returned at the end of the NTI days.

Hang in there, Musketeers! We'll get through this. We'll get through this together! #TogetherGC

shared_text:
Superintendent Traysea Moresea
March 25 at 11:10 AM ¬∑

Good late morning everyone,
I just want to send a quick message about a personal challenge. My family has been assisting with the direct care of my father-in-law while battling pancreatic cancer. This morning he lost his battle and we are grieving. At this time I have asked the central office team to cover any duties or needs that you may normally send directly to me. We did meet yesterday and revised some of our NTI services and that will be coming out publicly soon. My "Sit Down with the Superintendent" session has been canceled for this week. All communications will be going through the district main page until next week when I can return. Currently my family is taking my mother in law to my husband's home town in WV to mourn and prepare for private arrangements. I appreciate all that you are doing to take care of our GC families and I promise to be back on the front line soon. In the meantime take care of each other #TogetherGC #TogetherKY.

Love,
Traysea

Mckell Middle School
March 13 at 1:02 PM ¬∑

Parents and students, a great way to beat the boredom during our time off is to...READ!!! The public library offers a variety of online resources through which you can borrow books, watch movies, read magazines, etc. All you need is a library card. Below are links to some of the resources they offer. If at any time during this extended break you have any questions about access, etc. you can contact our librarian Mrs. Webster at (606) 932-3221 or through email at jenifer.webster@greenup.kyschools.us Stay tuned for videos from Mrs. Webster on how to use these resources at a later date and also contests for students.

KY LIBRARIES UNBOUND https://kyunbound.overdrive.com/boone-greenup/content --Check out books, read magazines, audiobooks, etc.

HOOPLA https://www.hoopladigital.com/ --Use your library card to access videos, magazines, books, audiobooks, etc

GREENUP COUNTY PUBLIC LIBRARIES http://www.youseemore.com/greenup/ --homepage of the Greenup County public library system where you have access to a variety of resources using your library card.

Matt Gilbert
March 12 at 11:00 PM ¬∑

Beginning Monday March 16th through March 27th, all Greenup County athletic participation ,including practices and competition, will be canceled while our students are out of school. All athletic facilities will be closed as well. Tomorrow, Friday, will be the last day for teams to hold outside practice only before we go on hiatus.

Our Coaches and I will be working to reschedule as many games and meets as possible and I will update everyone as any new information develops.

Although this may be a burden and we hate to lose our time on the field and court, safety remains our top priority for our student-athletes and athletic staffs!

Please do not hesitate to contact me if you have any questions or concerns. Thank you!

Greenup County High School Greenup Schools Wurtland Middle School- Greenup County Schools Mckell Middle School

What an amazing showing at the Northern Kentucky Science and Engineering Fair!
GCHS students, Gracie Terry and Matthew Diamond, received the Yale Science & Engineering Association Award for Most Outstanding Exhibit in Computer Science, Engineering, Physics, or Chemistry and are moving on to the Kentucky Science & Engineering Fair in March. They also received the Amazon Observer Award, which includes an all expense paid trip to Anaheim, California in May to attend the International Science and Engineering Fair!
MES students, Ella Stone and Charlie Grayson, won 1st place.
AES student, Mason Carr, took 2nd place
We are so proud of our Musketeers!
#GCMusketeerWay

post_text:
Congratulations to our District Food Fight Winners - McKell Elementary School! They collected an amazing 3,525 items for the Brown Bag program and the GCHS Food Bank! GCSD students collected 6,816 items across the district. We say it all the time, but we really do have the best kids! Here's the classroom winners across the district:
AES - Ms. Nemeth's class
GES - Ms. Conley's class
MES - Ms. Martin's and Ms. Wireman's classes (tie)
WES - Ms. Todd's class
MMS - Ms. Harbour's class
WMS - Ms. Spencer's class
GCHS - Ms. Bowling's and Ms. Greenslate's classes

A big thank you to our students, parents and community members who donated to event. You are helping to end hunger in GC!
